  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Two children is the main turning point",
        "body": "The national share of currently married women who want no more children or are sterilized was almost unchanged overall, at 57.3 percent in 2025 compared with 57.6 percent in 2022. The more revealing pattern is by family size. In 2025, only 26.1 percent of women with one living child wanted to stop childbearing, but the share rose to 63.3 percent among those with two living children and 78.4 percent among those with three. This makes the move from one to two children the clearest national transition point in the data."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Larger families show broad agreement about stopping",
        "body": "After three living children, the desire to limit childbearing is high across the national series: 85.8 percent at four children, 83.4 percent at five, and 89.5 percent at six or more. The six-or-more group also rose from 84.0 percent in 2022 to 89.5 percent in 2025. That increase does not change the overall national total much, but it sharpens the picture at higher parities: once families are large, most currently married women say they do not want additional children."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Residence matters most before the second child",
        "body": "Urban and rural totals were nearly identical in 2025, at 57.5 percent and 57.1 percent. The difference appears earlier in the family-size progression. Among women with one living child, 29.1 percent in urban areas wanted no more children compared with 22.2 percent in rural areas; among those with two living children, the urban-rural gap narrowed to 65.2 percent versus 61.0 percent. This suggests that residence is most useful for understanding when stopping preferences emerge, not whether they eventually become common."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Social gradients are clearer within family size than in totals",
        "body": "The 2025 totals by education and wealth do not form a simple ladder. For example, the total was 68.1 percent among women with Grades 1-6 education but 51.2 percent among women with college education, while wealth totals ranged only from 55.4 percent to 59.4 percent. Within the same family size, the contrasts are sharper: among women with two living children, the highest and fourth wealth quintiles were at 67.9 percent and 69.0 percent, compared with 54.2 percent in the lowest quintile. This is an inference from the table pattern, but the totals appear to mix stopping preferences with differences in how women are distributed across family sizes."
      },
      {
        "heading": "BARMM and Zamboanga Peninsula stand apart regionally",
        "body": "Regional variation is much wider than the national social breakdowns. In 2025, CAR had the highest total share at 63.7 percent, followed closely by MIMAROPA at 63.2 percent and Bicol at 62.3 percent. BARMM was much lower at 29.7 percent, and Zamboanga Peninsula was next lowest at 42.7 percent. The gap is visible across family sizes: at two living children, BARMM was 26.4 percent and Zamboanga Peninsula was 44.6 percent, compared with the national 63.3 percent; at three living children, they were 34.9 percent and 55.1 percent, compared with the national 78.4 percent."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Nationally, 57.3 percent of currently married women wanted no more children or were sterilized in 2025, almost unchanged from 57.6 percent in 2022.",
      "The strongest national transition is between one and two living children, rising from 26.1 percent to 63.3 percent in 2025.",
      "Regional differences are large, with CAR at 63.7 percent and BARMM at 29.7 percent in the 2025 total."
    ]
  }
